<Base title="Primary sources library" compactHeader={true}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">مكتبة المصادر</p>
  <h2>Primary sources library</h2>
  <p class="summary">A starter library of classical scholarly citations on the topics this site covers. Each entry names the scholar, the work, and where the cited position appears, with a brief excerpt or paraphrase. The aim is to give readers a foothold for going to the sources themselves rather than to substitute for them. Contributions and corrections are welcome via the GitHub issues link in the footer.</p>

  <p class="standards">Verification standard: every citation here points to a specific named work. Where the excerpt is verbatim from a recognised English translation, that is noted. Where it is an English paraphrase of an Arabic passage, the Arabic source is named and a reader who reads Arabic can verify directly. We do not invent attributions; we do not paraphrase as if it were a quote.</p>

  <h3>On the category of <em>bidʿah</em></h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Shāfiʿī</strong> (d. 204 AH) — narrated by al-Bayhaqī in <em>Manāqib al-Shāfiʿī</em></p>
    <p>"Innovations are of two kinds: praiseworthy innovation and blameworthy innovation. What agrees with the Sunnah is praiseworthy, and what opposes it is blameworthy" (<em>al-bidʿatu bidʿatān: bidʿatun maḥmūdah wa-bidʿatun madhmūma</em>). This is the foundational text in classical Sunnī <em>uṣūl al-fiqh</em> for the categorical distinction between <em>bidʿa ḥasana</em> and <em>bidʿa ḍalāla</em>.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>ʿUmar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb</strong> — Bukhārī, <em>Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī</em>, "Kitāb Ṣalāt al-Tarāwīḥ"</p>
    <p>Reacting to seeing congregational tarāwīḥ — which the Prophet ﷺ had performed only briefly, then ceased to perform in congregation lest it be made obligatory — ʿUmar said: "<em>niʿmati l-bidʿatu hādhihi</em> — what an excellent innovation this is." This narration is the textual basis for the classical Sunnī position that the term <em>bidʿa</em> is not exclusively pejorative; ʿUmar's usage establishes that a new institutional practice can be praiseworthy.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Nawawī</strong> (d. 676 AH) — <em>Sharḥ Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em>, on the ḥadīth "every innovation is misguidance"</p>
    <p>Al-Nawawī's commentary on this ḥadīth is the standard classical Shāfiʿī treatment: the Prophet's ﷺ statement is general in form but specific in intended scope; what it intends is innovation that contradicts the Sharīʿah, not every new occasion or arrangement. Al-Nawawī divides bidʿa into five fiqh categories — <em>wājib</em> (e.g., codifying the Qurʾān), <em>mandūb</em> (e.g., founding madrasas), <em>mubāḥ</em>, <em>makrūh</em>, and <em>ḥarām</em> — under the principle that the legal status of the innovated act is determined by its content, not by the fact of its newness.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>On the Mawlid</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Jalāl al-Dīn al-Suyūṭī</strong> (d. 911 AH) — <em>Ḥusn al-Maqṣid fī ʿAmal al-Mawlid</em></p>
    <p>The standard classical Sunnī treatise on the Mawlid. Al-Suyūṭī classes the Mawlid as a <em>bidʿa ḥasana</em> when it consists of recitation of Qurʾān, narration of the Prophet's ﷺ life, charity, and joy. He cites Ibn Diḥyah and Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī as fellow endorsers among the major early-15th-century Sunnī authorities. The work is brief, fully-cited, and remains the primary text consulted by classical Sunnī muftis on the question.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Ibn Ḥajar al-Haytamī</strong> (d. 974 AH) — <em>al-Iʿlām bi-Qawāṭiʿ al-Islām</em> and <em>al-Niʿmat al-Kubrā ʿalā al-ʿĀlam fī Mawlid Sayyid Walad Ādam</em></p>
    <p>Al-Haytamī, the leading Shāfiʿī muftī of late-Mamlūk Mecca, writes in defense of the Mawlid as a praiseworthy practice when conducted with Sharʿī decorum. He addresses and rebuts the prohibitionist arguments specifically.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>On tawassul and istighātha</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Tirmidhī</strong>, <em>Sunan al-Tirmidhī</em> 3578 — the ḥadīth of the blind man</p>
    <p>The Prophet ﷺ taught a blind man a duʿāʾ that includes the words: "<em>allāhumma innī asʾaluka wa-atawajjahu ilayka bi-Nabiyyika Muḥammad — yā Muḥammad, innī atawajjahu bika ilā rabbī fī ḥājatī hādhihi li-tuqḍā lī</em>" — "O Allāh, I ask You and turn to You by Your Prophet Muḥammad. O Muḥammad, I turn through you to my Lord with this need of mine, that it might be granted." Al-Tirmidhī graded the ḥadīth <em>ḥasan ṣaḥīḥ gharīb</em>. The wording is the foundational textual basis for tawassul through the Prophet's ﷺ rank.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>al-Ṭabarānī</strong> — <em>al-Muʿjam al-Kabīr</em>, narration of ʿUthmān ibn Ḥunayf</p>
    <p>ʿUthmān ibn Ḥunayf, the Companion who originally narrated the blind-man's duʿāʾ from the Prophet ﷺ, taught the same wording to a man with a need <em>after</em> the Prophet's ﷺ death — and the man's need was granted. This narration is the textual basis classical Sunnī scholars cite for the permissibility of tawassul through the Prophet ﷺ after his earthly life.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Taqī al-Dīn al-Subkī</strong> (d. 756 AH) — <em>Shifāʾ al-Saqām fī Ziyārat Khayr al-Anām</em></p>
    <p>Al-Subkī's full-length defense of tawassul, istighātha, and ziyāra of the Prophet ﷺ, written specifically against the Ibn Taymiyya line of restriction. The work goes through every relevant ḥadīth, the linguistic categories, and the four-madhhab fatwa positions. This is the standard classical Sunnī reference on the topic.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Ibn Ḥajar al-Haytamī</strong> (d. 974 AH) — <em>al-Jawhar al-Munaẓẓam fī Ziyārat al-Qabr al-Sharīf al-Nabawī al-Mukarram</em></p>
    <p>A second-generation classical Sunnī treatise on visiting the Prophet's ﷺ grave and the permissibility of tawassul through him. Al-Haytamī works through the same questions as al-Subkī with additional Mamlūk-era fatwa material.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>On visiting graves (ziyārat al-qubūr)</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Nawawī</strong> — <em>al-Adhkār</em>, "Bāb mā yaqūluhu zāʾir al-qubūr"</p>
    <p>The standard classical Shāfiʿī chapter on visiting graves, presenting the recommended decorum: the salām formula transmitted from the Prophet ﷺ ("<em>al-salāmu ʿalaykum dāra qawmin muʾminīn</em>"), recitation of Qurʾān whose reward is sent to the deceased, and the duʿāʾ for forgiveness. Al-Nawawī treats grave visitation as recommended (<em>mustaḥabb</em>) for both men and women within the conditions transmitted from the Salaf.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Ibn al-Ḥājj al-Mālikī</strong> (d. 737 AH) — <em>al-Madkhal</em>, vol. 1, "Faṣl fī Ziyārat al-Qubūr"</p>
    <p>The classical Mālikī manual on devotional decorum. Ibn al-Ḥājj treats grave visitation extensively, including its permissibility and its limits — particularly his characteristic warnings against syncretic or excessive practices that the Mālikī tradition had encountered in its 8th-century Maghribī context.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>On group dhikr</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Nawawī</strong> — <em>al-Adhkār</em>, "Bāb al-Dhikr ba'd al-Ṣalāh", citing Bukhārī and Muslim</p>
    <p>The Companion Ibn ʿAbbās narrated: "We used to know that the prayer of the Prophet ﷺ had ended by the dhikr [raised in the masjid afterwards]" (<em>kunnā naʿrifu inqiḍāʾ ṣalāt al-Nabī ﷺ bi-l-takbīr</em>). Al-Nawawī cites this as the textual basis for the permissibility of audible collective dhikr after the obligatory prayer in congregation.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Suyūṭī</strong> — <em>Natījat al-Fikar fī al-Jahr bi-l-Dhikr</em></p>
    <p>Al-Suyūṭī's specific treatise on raising the voice in dhikr — addressing both individual and collective contexts. He gathers the Qurʾānic and ḥadīth texts on the virtue of dhikr in groups (notably the ḥadīth of the angels surrounding gatherings of dhikr) and concludes that audible collective dhikr is permitted within Sharʿī decorum.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>On the divine attributes (ʿaqīdah)</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Abū Jaʿfar al-Ṭaḥāwī</strong> (d. 321 AH) — <em>al-ʿAqīda al-Ṭaḥāwiyya</em></p>
    <p>The most widely-accepted Sunnī creedal text — used by Atharī, Ashʿarī, and Māturīdī scholars alike. The relevant passage on transcendence: Allāh is exalted above limits, ends, organs, and instruments; the six directions do not contain Him as they contain all created things. The work is short (~75 brief paragraphs) and is the natural starting point for any reader new to Sunnī ʿaqīdah.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Abū al-Ḥasan al-Ashʿarī</strong> (d. 324 AH) — <em>al-Ibāna ʿan Uṣūl al-Diyāna</em></p>
    <p>Al-Ashʿarī's late creedal manual, written after his return from Muʿtazilism to mainstream Sunnism. Ascribed to the Atharī line by Salafī scholars and read alongside al-Ashʿarī's earlier kalām-based works by classical Ashʿarīs. The textual situation itself is part of the disagreement.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Bayhaqī</strong> (d. 458 AH) — <em>al-Asmāʾ wa-l-Ṣifāt</em></p>
    <p>The most extensive classical Sunnī treatment of the divine names and attributes, working through every relevant Qurʾānic verse and ḥadīth and presenting the early Sunnī positions on each. Al-Bayhaqī's discussion of the verses on <em>istiwāʾ</em>, <em>yad</em>, <em>wajh</em>, and <em>nuzūl</em> is the standard reference for the classical Sunnī range — affirmation with <em>tafwīḍ</em>, with <em>ta'wīl</em> where necessary to negate <em>tashbīh</em>.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>On taqlīd of a madhhab</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Ghazālī</strong> (d. 505 AH) — <em>al-Mustaṣfā min ʿIlm al-Uṣūl</em></p>
    <p>Al-Ghazālī's <em>uṣūl al-fiqh</em> manual. The standard classical Sunnī treatment of the relationship between the qualified <em>mujtahid</em> and the <em>muqallid</em> (the follower). Al-Ghazālī sets out the conditions under which a Muslim is required to do taqlīd of a recognised madhhab — that is, the great majority of Muslims — and the conditions under which ijtihād becomes obligatory rather than optional.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Nawawī</strong> — introduction to <em>al-Majmūʿ Sharḥ al-Muhadhdhab</em></p>
    <p>The standard classical Shāfiʿī articulation of the <em>muqallid</em>'s obligation: the lay Muslim must follow one of the recognised four madhāhib in their Sharʿī rulings, since the alternative — direct ijtihād from the Qurʾān and Sunnah by the unqualified — produces religious chaos. The argument is part of the classical Sunnī defense of the four-madhhab framework.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>How this library will grow</h3>

  <p>This is a starter list. Topics not yet covered here that a future expansion could include: the Caliphate and political ʿaqīdah, the conditions and ranks of <em>ijtihād</em>, the specific positions of the four madhāhib on contested fiqh questions, the Ashʿarī/Māturīdī differences, and the Salafī primary sources (Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb, Albānī, ibn Bāz) presented in their own words. To suggest an addition or flag a misattribution, open an issue on the project's GitHub repository (link in the footer).</p>
